         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">The sprig sent from St. Arnaud ¶ Vic. ¶  is from the British white poplar (Populus alba), which occurs with some variability as regards the intenseness of its white vestiture and the degree of indenta...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">95.10.00e</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To the Leader</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Letter not found. The text given here is from 'Answers to correspondents', <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Leader</seg>, 19 October 1895, p. 13 (B95.10.09). It was introduced by <seg style="font-variant: small-caps; ">'</seg>
                     <seg style="font-variant: small-caps; ">Leaves of Tree</seg>
                     <seg style="">. —32, St. Arnaud.— Baron von Mueller favors us with the following reply:—'.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
               <seg style="">
                  <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The sprig sent from St. Arnaud</seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                     <p rend="Footnote"
                        style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Vic.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <seg style=""> is from the British white poplar (<name key="Populus%20alba">Populus alba</name>), which occurs with some variability as regards the intenseness of its white vestiture and the degree of indentation of the leaves. The tree reaches from Britain to Sweden, Siberia, the Himalayan Mountains, and the countries at the Mediterranean Sea. I planted it near Melbourne in the 50th year of this century; it is an excellent tree for summer shade, easily grown, of attractive coloration, and easily propagated from </seg>cuttings.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Populus%20alba">Populus alba</name>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
         </div>
